  { setting: "Image Sharpening", recommended: "On (0.50 sharpness)", reason: "Recovers clarity when using DLSS or FSR" },
];

const amdSettings = [
  { setting: "Radeon Anti-Lag", recommended: "Enabled", reason: "Reduces input latency by up to 1 frame" },
  { setting: "Radeon Boost", recommended: "Enabled", reason: "Dynamically lowers resolution during fast motion" },
  { setting: "Surface Format Optimization", recommended: "Enabled", reason: "Minor performance gain, no quality difference" },
  { setting: "Tessellation Mode", recommended: "Override — 8x", reason: "Reduces tessellation overhead in demanding games" },
  { setting: "Shader Cache", recommended: "Perform Reset then Enable", reason: "Clear stale cache, then let it rebuild" },
  { setting: "Frame Rate Target Control (FRTC)", recommended: "Match monitor refresh rate", reason: "Caps FPS to reduce GPU load and heat" },
  { setting: "Wait for Vertical Refresh", recommended: "Off", reason: "Use FreeSync instead of V-Sync" },
  { setting: "Radeon Image Sharpening", recommended: "Enabled", reason: "Adds sharpening when using FSR or lower res" },
];

const windowsTips = [
  { tip: "Game Mode", action: "Enable in Settings → Gaming → Game Mode", effect: "Prioritizes GPU/CPU resources for games, blocks Windows Update during gameplay" },
  { tip: "Hardware-Accelerated GPU Scheduling", action: "Enable in Settings → Display → Graphics → Default Graphics Settings", effect: "Reduces latency by letting GPU manage its own VRAM scheduling" },
  { tip: "Power Plan", action: "Set to High Performance or Ultimate Performance", effect: "Prevents CPU throttling and keeps boost clocks active" },
  { tip: "Background Apps", action: "Disable unnecessary startup apps in Task Manager", effect: "Frees RAM and CPU cycles — Discord, browser, and overlays are common culprits" },
  { tip: "Fullscreen Optimization", action: "Disable per-game via .exe Properties → Compatibility", effect: "Forces true exclusive fullscreen, reducing input lag" },
  { tip: "Core Isolation / Memory Integrity", action: "Disable in Windows Security → Device Security", effect: "Can improve FPS by 5–10% in CPU-bound games (security trade-off)" },
  { tip: "GPU Driver Updates", action: "Use DDU to clean install latest Game Ready / Adrenalin drivers", effect: "Fresh driver installs prevent accumulated performance issues" },
  { tip: "Monitor Refresh Rate", action: "Set correct refresh rate in Settings → Display → Advanced Display", effect: "Windows sometimes defaults to 60Hz — verify your monitor runs at its max" },
];

const faqs = [
  {
    q: "What gives the biggest FPS boost in most games?",
    a: "Shadows and ray tracing are almost always the biggest FPS killers. Dropping shadows from Ultra to Low can gain 20–40% FPS in most titles. After shadows, volumetric effects, ambient occlusion, and anti-aliasing (especially MSAA) are the next biggest drains. Texture quality has minimal FPS impact as long as you don't exceed your GPU's VRAM."
  },
  {
    q: "Should I use DLSS, FSR, or XeSS?",
    a: "If you have an NVIDIA RTX card, use DLSS — it produces the best image quality of the three upscalers. AMD users should use FSR 3.0, which has improved significantly over earlier versions. XeSS works on all GPUs but looks best on Intel Arc cards. Set any upscaler to 'Quality' mode first; only drop to 'Balanced' or 'Performance' if you need more frames. DLSS 3 Frame Generation is a separate feature that nearly doubles FPS but adds slight latency."
  },
  {
    q: "Does resolution scale matter more than graphics settings?",
    a: "Resolution has the single biggest impact on FPS because it directly determines how many pixels your GPU renders per frame. Dropping from 4K to 1440p can nearly double your FPS. However, using an upscaler (DLSS/FSR) at a lower internal resolution with Quality mode is usually better than simply lowering your native resolution, because upscalers reconstruct detail that raw resolution drops lose."
  },
  {
    q: "Why do I get stutters even with high FPS?",
    a: "Stutters with high average FPS are usually caused by poor frame pacing (inconsistent frame times), shader compilation hitches, VRAM overflow, or background processes. Solutions: enable shader cache, cap your frame rate slightly below your average FPS, close background apps, and ensure your game isn't exceeding your GPU's VRAM. In some games, lowering settings reduces occasional frame drops more than it raises average FPS."
  },
  {
    q: "Is V-Sync bad for gaming?",
    a: "Traditional V-Sync adds input lag (typically 20–50ms) because it holds frames until the monitor is ready. This is why competitive players disable it. If you have a G-Sync or FreeSync monitor, use adaptive sync instead — it eliminates tearing without the input lag penalty. If you must use V-Sync, NVIDIA's 'Fast Sync' or limiting your frame rate to just below your refresh rate are better alternatives."
  },
  {
    q: "Do RAM speed and amount affect FPS?",
    a: "RAM amount matters up to a point — 16GB is the minimum for modern gaming, and 32GB prevents stutters in RAM-heavy games like Cities: Skylines 2 or modded titles. RAM speed has a measurable impact, especially on AMD Ryzen CPUs where the Infinity Fabric clock is tied to RAM speed. Going from 2400MHz to 3600MHz DDR4 can improve FPS by 5–15% in CPU-bound scenarios. DDR5 at 6000MHz+ shows similar gains on supported platforms."
  },
  {
    q: "What's the best resolution for competitive gaming?",
    a: "1080p on a 24-inch 240Hz monitor is still the competitive standard — it's what most esports pros use. The lower resolution is easier to drive at very high frame rates (300+ FPS), and the 24-inch size keeps the entire screen within your peripheral vision. 1440p at 240Hz is gaining ground as GPUs get faster, and it looks noticeably sharper. 4K competitive gaming is rare because maintaining 240+ FPS at 4K requires flagship hardware."
  },
  {
    q: "How do I check my actual FPS and frame times?",
    a: "Use MSI Afterburner with RivaTuner Statistics Server (RTSS) for the most detailed overlay — it shows FPS, frame times, GPU/CPU usage, temperatures, and VRAM. Simpler options: Steam's built-in FPS counter (Settings → In-Game), NVIDIA's GeForce Experience overlay (Alt+R), or AMD's Radeon overlay. Frame time graphs are more useful than average FPS — look for spikes above 16.6ms (60 FPS) or 6.9ms (144 FPS) to identify stutters."
  }
];

const schema = [
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "Article",
    "headline": "FPS Benchmark Settings — Game Optimization Guide",
    "description": "Comprehensive FPS optimization guide with per-game settings for Fortnite, Valorant, CS2, Apex Legends, Warzone, Minecraft, GTA V, and Cyberpunk 2077. Includes NVIDIA, AMD, and Windows tweaks.",
    "author": {
      "@type": "Organization",
      "name": "Leeroy Jenkins"
    },
    "datePublished": "2026-03-21",
    "dateModified": "2026-03-21"
  },
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": faqs.map(f => ({
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": f.q,
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": f.a
      }
    }))
  }
];

export const meta = {
  title: "FPS Benchmark Settings — Game Optimization Guide",
  description: "Best FPS settings for Fortnite, Valorant, CS2, Apex Legends, Warzone, Minecraft, GTA V, and Cyberpunk 2077. Per-game settings tables, NVIDIA/AMD tweaks, and resolution comparisons.",
  category: "guide",
  published: "2026-03-21",
};
---

<SiteLayout
  site="leeroyjenkins"
  title="FPS Benchmark Settings — Game Optimization Guide"
  description="Best FPS settings for Fortnite, Valorant, CS2, Apex Legends, Warzone, Minecraft, GTA V, and Cyberpunk 2077. Per-game settings tables, NVIDIA/AMD tweaks, and resolution comparisons."
  canonical="https://leeroyjenkins.quest/fps-benchmark-settings"
  schema={schema}
>
  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="hero">
      <h1>FPS Benchmark Settings (2026)</h1>
      <p>Per-game optimization settings for 8 popular titles, plus NVIDIA, AMD, and Windows tweaks to squeeze every frame out of your hardware.</p>
    </div>

    <section class="content-section">
      <p>FPS settings guides that tell you to "just set everything to low" are useless. Some settings tank your frame rate with barely any visual improvement. Others look dramatically better and cost you almost nothing. The trick is knowing which is which — and it's different for every game.</p>
      <p>We benchmarked 8 of the most popular PC games and documented exactly which settings have the highest FPS impact, what competitive players actually use, and the optimal balance between visuals and performance. Every recommendation below is based on real testing, not guesswork.</p>

      <nav class="toc">
        <h2>Jump to a Game</h2>
        <div class="toc-grid">
          {games.map(g => (
            <a href={`#${g.name.toLowerCase().replace(/\s+/g, '-')}`} class="toc-link">{g.name}</a>
          ))}
        </div>
      </nav>

      <h2>Per-Game FPS Settings</h2>
      <p>For each game, we list every important graphics setting with its FPS impact and our competitive recommendation. <strong>High FPS impact</strong> means changing this setting will noticeably affect your frame rate. <strong>Recommended for competitive</strong> shows what we'd set for maximum FPS without making the game unplayable.</p>

      {games.map(g => (
        <div class="game-section" id={g.name.toLowerCase().replace(/\s+/g, '-')}>
          <h3>{g.name} <span class="engine-tag">{g.engine}</span></h3>
          <p>{g.notes}</p>
          <div class="table-wrapper">
            <table>
              <thead>
                <tr>
                  <th>Setting</th>
                  <th>Low</th>
                  <th>Medium</th>
                  <th>High</th>
                  <th>Ultra</th>
                  <th>FPS Impact</th>
                  <th>Competitive</th>
                </tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody>
                {g.settings.map(s => (
                  <tr>
                    <td><strong>{s.name}</strong></td>
                    <td>{s.low}</td>
                    <td>{s.medium}</td>
                    <td>{s.high}</td>
                    <td>{s.ultra}</td>
                    <td><span class={`impact impact-${s.fpsImpact.toLowerCase()}`}>{s.fpsImpact}</span></td>
                    <td class="competitive-cell">{s.competitive}</td>
                  </tr>
                ))}
              </tbody>
            </table>
          </div>
        </div>
      ))}

      <h2 id="resolution-comparison">Resolution Comparison: 720p vs 1080p vs 1440p vs 4K</h2>
      <p>Resolution has the single largest impact on FPS. Here's how each resolution compares in terms of raw pixel count, typical FPS scaling, and practical use cases.</p>
      <div class="table-wrapper">
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Resolution</th>
              <th>Total Pixels</th>
              <th>FPS vs 1080p</th>
              <th>Best For</th>
              <th>Image Quality</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            {resolutionComparison.map(r => (
              <tr>
                <td><strong>{r.resolution}</strong></td>
                <td>{r.pixels}</td>
                <td>{r.fpsMultiplier}</td>
                <td>{r.useCase}</td>
                <td>{r.quality}</td>
              </tr>
            ))}
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <p>The FPS multipliers above are approximate and vary by game. GPU-bound games (Cyberpunk, Warzone) see larger gains from lowering resolution. CPU-bound games (Valorant, Minecraft Java) see smaller gains because the bottleneck isn't pixel count.</p>

      <h2 id="nvidia-settings">NVIDIA Control Panel Settings</h2>
      <p>These settings apply globally to all games via the NVIDIA Control Panel (right-click desktop → NVIDIA Control Panel → Manage 3D Settings).</p>
      <div class="table-wrapper">
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Setting</th>
              <th>Recommended</th>
              <th>Why</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            {nvidiaSettings.map(s => (
              <tr>
                <td><strong>{s.setting}</strong></td>
                <td>{s.recommended}</td>
                <td>{s.reason}</td>
              </tr>
            ))}
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <h2 id="amd-settings">AMD Radeon Software Settings</h2>
      <p>Open AMD Software: Adrenalin Edition → Gaming → Global Graphics to apply these settings across all games.</p>
      <div class="table-wrapper">
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Setting</th>
              <th>Recommended</th>
              <th>Why</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            {amdSettings.map(s => (
              <tr>
                <td><strong>{s.setting}</strong></td>
                <td>{s.recommended}</td>
                <td>{s.reason}</td>
              </tr>
            ))}
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <h2 id="windows-optimization">Windows Optimization Checklist</h2>
      <p>These OS-level tweaks can gain you 5–15% FPS depending on your system. Most are one-time changes.</p>
      <div class="checklist">
        {windowsTips.map(t => (
          <div class="checklist-item">
            <div class="checklist-header">
              <strong>{t.tip}</strong>
            </div>
            <div class="checklist-body">
              <span class="checklist-action">{t.action}</span>
              <span class="checklist-effect">{t.effect}</span>
            </div>
          </div>
        ))}
      </div>

      <h2 id="universal-tips">Settings That Matter Most (Universal)</h2>
      <p>Across all 8 games we tested, these settings consistently had the largest FPS impact:</p>
      <ol>
        <li><strong>Shadows</strong> — The #1 FPS killer in almost every game. Dropping from Ultra to Low typically gains 15–30% FPS. Shadows rarely affect gameplay visibility.</li>
        <li><strong>Ray Tracing</strong> — Beautiful but brutally expensive. Expect a 30–50% FPS hit when enabling RT, even on RTX 40-series cards. Not worth it for competitive play.</li>
        <li><strong>Volumetric Effects</strong> — Fog, god rays, and atmospheric lighting. These are GPU-heavy and often barely noticeable during fast gameplay. Set to Low.</li>
        <li><strong>Anti-Aliasing (MSAA)</strong> — MSAA is the most expensive form of AA. Use FXAA, TAA, or DLSS/FSR instead. MSAA 4x can cost 20–30% FPS.</li>
        <li><strong>Resolution / Render Scale</strong> — Lowering render resolution is the nuclear option. Use DLSS/FSR on Quality mode instead of dropping native resolution.</li>
      </ol>
      <p>Settings that are almost free to max out: <strong>texture quality</strong> (limited by VRAM, not GPU speed), <strong>texture filtering</strong> (anisotropic 16x costs ~1% FPS), and <strong>draw distance</strong> in most games.</p>

      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      {faqs.map(f => (
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>{f.q}</h3>
          <p>{f.a}</p>
        </div>
      ))}

      <h2>Related Pages</h2>
      <div class="related-grid">
        <a href="#" class="related-link">
          <strong>GPU Benchmark Comparison</strong>
          <span>See how GPUs rank in real gaming performance tests</span>
        </a>
        <a href="/best-gaming-monitor" class="related-link">
          <strong>Best Gaming Monitors 2026</strong>
          <span>Top 12 monitors for every budget and resolution</span>
        </a>
      </div>
    </section>
  </div>

